summary: Pokemon Card of the Day #1548: Stunfisk (Noble Victories #68)
title: Pokemon Card of the Day #1548: Stunfisk (Noble Victories #68)
body:
Stunfisk was just a strange Pokemon. It was a Ground/Electric-type Pokemon based off a fish. This meant that it couldn’t be a surprise when a Stunfisk came out that used one type of Energy while being a completely different type. It brought variety, at least. That variety, of course, had to be on a good Pokemon, and Stunfisk did have some problems to work through.

90 HP wasn’t bad for a Basic Pokemon. It was just low enough to be vulnerable to the likes of Darkrai EX and Terrakion, however, and it wasn’t hard for Mewtwo EX to reach that number as well, so it was still tough to survive in such a format. The Water Weakness could matter if up against something like Vanilluxe, Kyurem, or the later Keldeo EX. At least there was a Lightning Resistance, which was nice against some of the weaker Lightning-types but not quite enough against Zekrom. Stunfisk had one good stat, a Retreat Cost that was just 1.

Trickle was a flip-based attack. A Lightning and a Colorless Energy gave you 2 flips, and 30 damage was done for each heads. This was pretty sad.

Thundershock wasn’t much better. 50 damage for 2 Lightning and a Colorless looked more like an attack from 2001. It did have a flip for Paralysis but it just wasn’t enough.

Stunfisk looked interesting since it was a Pokemon that could hit Fighting-type Weaknesses in Lightning decks. It was, however, still weaker against those Pokemon than the neutral Zekrom was. This meant that Stunfisk was just an amusing side note more than a real deck option.

summary: Pokemon Cinematic Universe a Possibility After Detective Pikachu - IGN
title: Pokemon Cinematic Universe a Possibility After Detective Pikachu - IGN
excerpt: A Detective Pikachu producer gives hope for a live-action Pokemon Cinematic Universe. Here's what she said.
description:
Well, we have official confirmation that Legendary Entertainment are considering a full blown live-action Pokémon franchise, assuming Detective Pikachu does well (Which I think that’s a given at this point). It’s a vague answer yes, but considering a Detective Pikachu sequel was already announced almost 2 months ago now, this is a positive sign.

Pokémon Colosseum movie when? :D

(Side note, I have to laugh at he bit about there only being 19 movies and 6 seasons of the Pokémon anime. Like… wow, failed a google search there, didn’t ya XD)

tags: apparently it's homophobic to prove people wrong???
summary: When someone makes a post claiming that Fennel is Professor Juniper's wife and you say that she canonically is just a friend...
body:
When someone makes a post claiming that Fennel is Professor Juniper’s wife and you say that she canonically is just a friend because Game Freak/Nintendo wouldn’t have put a queer character in because Japan is still really homophobic as a country, and even if she WAS, bulbapedia wouldn’t have missed it, and some dumbass goes “bulbapedia DIDN’T miss it tho!!” And sends you this clearly edited screenshot and calls you homophobic:

As opposed to the actual screenshot from Bulbapedia:

10,000 gullible idiots reblogged the baseless “she’s queer!” Claim without fact checking it, by the way. It’s also really mature to create false things and block people before you can prove them wrong, but that’s Tumblr I guess

blog.title: P̵o̵K̸é̴G̸o̸D̷s̸ and Frightful Things to Come?
blog.description: There is a growing desire and expectation of humans here on Earth in making full contact with PoKéMoN who are still unknown. Back in 1995, when I saw my first UPM (Unindexed Pocket Monster), I found out very quickly that other people thought you were totally crazy if you said you saw such things. The world has changed quite a bit since then when I was a child. In fact, in late 1997, a poll taken in Kanto shows that for the first time ever, more than fifty percent of residents now believe in PokéGODS's. Since then, there have been polls that put the figure at over eighty percent or more.
